{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Faculty members affiliated with U.S. colleges and universities that aspire to eminence must \"publish or perish.\"",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The process of deciding which books should be published favors authors who are associated with the most prestigious universities and other research institutions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Some think this bias could be minimized if the pre-publication reviewing of academic books included commitments to objectivity like those built into reviewing academic articles for journals.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The academic and the publishing industries promote the hierarchy of perceived excellence that dominates the process of publishing academic books.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Nor can any such showing be made by simply applying some standard-offering ethical system, because ethics has become too focused on individual decision making to address institutional arrangements appropriately.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Editors of journals and collections ordinarily send article manuscripts (which I will hereafter call papers) to reviewers without identifying either the author or her institutional affiliation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The intended reason for this attention to anonymity is, of course, to level the playing field among scholars regardless of who they are or what their institutional affiliation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Clearly though, the practice does not conform to the principle.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "A kind of top-down bias, then, permeates and orchestrates the paper reviewing process.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "In contrast to the anonymity approach to paper reviewing, book reviewing in philosophy (as in other disciplines) is altogether transparent.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The reviewer of a book manuscript, however chosen, knows from the outset the real name of the author.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "If the author is affiliated with a lower echelon institution, the reviewer will be tempted to assume at the outset that it is of inferior quality.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "It seems, then, that the prepublication screening of academics' book manuscripts is more restrictive than is the screening of papers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Given this state of affairs, many academics, especially in philosophy, can probably tell at least one story about having a book manuscript rejected.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "As noted above, anyone partial to fundamental fairness, opportunity, and equal respect must find the transparency of academic book reviewing ethically troublesome.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The principal internal argument focuses on the well-being of a discipline, which as practiced, constitutes a profession.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "This domination still prevails to the advantage of the top-echelon universities with which those who make up this professional elite are affiliated as faculty and/or former doctoral students.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
